name: **_Oileán Dá Bhranóg_**
description: Oileán Dá Bhranóg L769-118 Sheet 51 The more E of the Brannock Islands. Minutes from Bungowla on Inishmore, this is a much more pleasant place which enjoys few tourists. There is room for many tents, on reasonably good camping ground. Lots of driftwood for campfires. Fair Pollack fishing in the landing bay. The landing is easy onto a stony beach in a bay (An Caladh) on the S side, sheltered by two large flat offliers. No houses and no water supply. Donkies, seals, gulls. Note that the following information is received second-hand, and may not be relied upon as fully as elsewhere. It was researched from Tim Robinson’s ‘Stones of Aran’. He says the ‘most magnificent piece of Aran’s cliff-architecture’ – a sea cave with pillars and holes in the roof – is on the E side. Not yet found by modern kayakers.
